<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
	Debug-only entitlements for the Mac target. Intentionally OMITS
	`com.apple.security.app-sandbox` so XCUITest's runner can establish
	its XPC connection to the host app for the integration harness â€”
	sandboxed Mac apps can't be UI-tested without ad-hoc signing +
	provisioning gymnastics, and the harness is the higher-value
	tradeoff. Release entitlements (MatronMac.entitlements) DO include
	`com.apple.security.app-sandbox` for App Store distribution.

	Acknowledged risk: sandbox-related bugs (Keychain scoping, file-
	system access, network behaviour) won't surface in Debug builds â€”
	they only show up at Release / TestFlight. Mitigation is manual
	smoke on signed Release builds (per the Phase 3 workflow in
	docs/HANDOVER.md). Per-config wiring lives in project.yml at the
	MatronMac target's settings.configs.Debug / settings.configs.Release
	split.

	If a future review re-flags the missing app-sandbox entitlement,
	the answer is: yes, intentional; see the project.yml comment block
	at the MatronMac target settings.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
	<key>com.apple.security.network.client</key>
	<true/>
	<key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-only</key>
	<true/>
	<!--
		Keychain access group, parity with Release. Required for
		`RecoveryKeyManager.generateAndPersist` to write the recovery
		key into the user's Keychain â€” without it, `SecItemAdd` returns
		errSecMissingEntitlement (-34018) on every call and the user
		sees "Couldn't auto-store your recovery key" inline. The group
		string uses Xcode's `$(AppIdentifierPrefix)` build-time
		substitution; ad-hoc-signed harness builds (which set
		CODE_SIGN_IDENTITY=-) won't validate it (the entitlement is
		checked against the AppID at runtime), so they'll still hit
		-34018 â€” but the view-model already handles that path via
		`PersistenceError.keychainWriteFailedButKeyAvailable`. Properly
		signed dev builds (Personal Team or the org team)
		get a working Keychain write at runtime.
	-->
	<key>keychain-access-groups</key>
	<array>
		<string>$(AppIdentifierPrefix)chat.matron.mac</string>
	</array>
	<!--
		Phase 4 Task 12: APNs environment for Debug builds. Pairs with
		`use_sandbox: true` on the matching Sygnal `app_id`
		(`chat.matron.mac.dev`). Mismatch (Debug build hitting an
		`app_id` mapped to `use_sandbox: false`) silently rejects the
		token at Sygnal with `{"rejected": [<token>]}` and never
		reaches APNs â€” hard to diagnose live. The entitlement-vs-app_id
		pairing is pinned on both sides; see
		`docs/superpowers/plans/2026-05-02-matron-ios-phase-4-push-nse.md`
		Â§"Push setup runbook" for the cross-check.

		**macOS-specific key**: macOS uses
		`com.apple.developer.aps-environment` (NOT the iOS-only bare
		`aps-environment`). Initial Task 12 commit landed the iOS form
		on Mac, which fails to grant push capability â€” `NSApplication.registerForRemoteNotifications()`
		never produces a token. Bug spotted by cursor on PR #5 review;
		the right key per Apple's macOS entitlements docs is the
		`com.apple.developer.*` namespaced form.
	-->
	<key>com.apple.developer.aps-environment</key>
	<string>development</string>
</dict>
</plist>
